1
00:00:05,839 --> 00:00:08,759
There's still no word
from inside Downing Street.

2
00:00:12,763 --> 00:00:15,349
Though we are getting
even more new arrivals.

3
00:00:19,269 --> 00:00:21,146
We are the Slitheen.

4
00:00:21,438 --> 00:00:24,566
Reduce the Earth to
molten slag then sell it.

5
00:00:24,691 --> 00:00:26,777
Leave this planet
or I'll stop you.

6
00:00:30,197 --> 00:00:31,657
The world is in your hands.

7
00:00:49,550 --> 00:00:52,886
I've checked the figures.
I've checked them again and again.

8
00:00:53,011 --> 00:00:55,013
Always the same result.

9
00:00:55,847 --> 00:01:00,018
The design is not safe.
It could result in the death of millions.

10
00:01:01,061 --> 00:01:05,983
I beg of you, stop the project right now
before it's too late.

11
00:01:06,692 --> 00:01:08,944
MARGARET: Well, goodness me!

12
00:01:11,154 --> 00:01:14,074
Obviously, Mr Cleaver,
you're the expert.

13
00:01:14,575 --> 00:01:16,410
Then, you'll stop it?

14
00:01:17,619 --> 00:01:19,746
It seems I have no choice.

15
00:01:21,123 --> 00:01:22,833
(RUMBLING)

16
00:01:23,250 --> 00:01:26,003
Oh, do excuse me.

17
00:01:26,587 --> 00:01:29,006
Civic duties leave little time
for a sandwich.

18
00:01:29,089 --> 00:01:31,174
But you promise
you'll stop it today?

19
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:33,468
Well, of course!

20
00:01:33,594 --> 00:01:36,346
Nothing is more
important than human life.

21
00:01:38,348 --> 00:01:41,518
What do you take me for?
Some sort of maniac?

22
00:01:42,311 --> 00:01:43,395
Why, no.

23
00:01:43,478 --> 00:01:47,441
Am I right in thinking
you've shown your results only to me?

24
00:01:47,858 --> 00:01:51,111
-Just to you, no one else.
-Wise move.

25
00:01:51,361 --> 00:01:54,364
I can't tell you, Mrs Blaine,
this is such a weight off my mind.

26
00:01:54,489 --> 00:01:57,784
I've barely slept.
I couldn't believe my own readings.

27
00:01:57,868 --> 00:02:02,664
The scale of it. Destruction like
the British Isles has never seen before.

28
00:02:04,333 --> 00:02:05,459
If I didn't know better,

29
00:02:05,542 --> 00:02:08,253
I'd almost think that someone
wanted this project to go wrong.

30
00:02:08,337 --> 00:02:12,341
As though they intended this city
should be wiped off the map.

31
00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:19,473
Thank goodness we've got you,
our esteemed leader.

32
00:02:20,307 --> 00:02:21,933
(MR CLEAVER SCREAMING)

33
00:02:25,395 --> 00:02:27,481
(DOCTOR WHO THEME MUSIC)

34
00:03:38,885 --> 00:03:40,095
Who the hell are you?

35
00:03:40,554 --> 00:03:42,639
What do you mean, who the hell am I?
Who the hell are you?

36
00:03:42,764 --> 00:03:45,392
Captain Jack Harkness.
Whatever you're selling, we're not buying.

37
00:03:45,517 --> 00:03:46,601
Get out of my way!

38
00:03:47,811 --> 00:03:49,771
Don't tell me,
this must be Mickey.

39
00:03:49,896 --> 00:03:51,815
Here comes trouble.
How you doing, Ricky boy?

40
00:03:51,898 --> 00:03:54,526
-It's Mickey.
-Don't listen to him, he's winding you up.

41
00:03:54,609 --> 00:03:56,403
You look fantastic.

42
00:03:56,653 --> 00:04:00,198
Aw, sweet. Look at these two.
How come I never get any of that?

43
00:04:00,282 --> 00:04:02,451
-Buy me a drink first.
-You're such hard work.

44
00:04:02,534 --> 00:04:03,744
But worth it.

45
00:04:03,827 --> 00:04:05,954
Did you manage to find it?

46
00:04:06,037 --> 00:04:07,831
-There you go.
-I can go anywhere now.

47
00:04:07,914 --> 00:04:09,624
I've told you,
you don't need a passport.

48
00:04:09,708 --> 00:04:12,669
It's all very well
going to Platform One and Justicia

49
00:04:12,753 --> 00:04:16,131
and the Glass Pyramid of San Kaloon,
but what if we end up in Brazil?

50
00:04:16,214 --> 00:04:19,384
I might need it.
You see, I'm prepared for anything.

51
00:04:19,468 --> 00:04:21,470
Sounds like you're staying, then.

52
00:04:26,850 --> 00:04:30,061
So, what are you doing in Cardiff?
And who the hell's Jumping Jack Flash?

53
00:04:30,145 --> 00:04:32,147
I don't mind you hanging out
with Big Ears up there.

54
00:04:32,230 --> 00:04:33,857
-Oi!
-Look in the mirror.

55
00:04:34,566 --> 00:04:37,319
-But this guy, I don't know, he's kind of...
-Handsome?

56
00:04:37,402 --> 00:04:38,612
More like cheesy.

57
00:04:38,695 --> 00:04:41,948
Early 21st century slang.
Is cheesy good or bad?

58
00:04:42,032 --> 00:04:44,659
-It's bad.
-But bad means good, isn't that right?

59
00:04:44,743 --> 00:04:45,952
You saying I'm not handsome?

60
00:04:46,036 --> 00:04:48,330
We've just stopped off,
we need to refuel.

61
00:04:48,413 --> 00:04:51,875
The thing is, Cardiff's got this rift
running through the middle of the city.

62
00:04:51,958 --> 00:04:55,462
It's invisible, but it's like an earthquake fault
between different dimensions.

63
00:04:55,545 --> 00:04:57,047
The rift was healed back in 1869...

64
00:04:57,130 --> 00:04:59,883
Thanks to a girl named Gwyneth
because these creatures called the Gelth

65
00:05:00,008 --> 00:05:03,136
were using the rift as a gateway,
but she saved the world and closed it.

66
00:05:03,220 --> 00:05:06,097
But closing a rift always leaves a scar
and that scar generates energy,

67
00:05:06,181 --> 00:05:07,432
harmless to the human race...

68
00:05:07,516 --> 00:05:08,600
But perfect for the Tardis.

69
00:05:08,683 --> 00:05:11,520
Just park here for a couple of days,
right on top of the scar and...

70
00:05:11,603 --> 00:05:13,730
Open up the engines,
soak up the radiation...

71
00:05:13,814 --> 00:05:15,899
Like filling her up
with petrol and off we go.

72
00:05:15,982 --> 00:05:18,068
-Into time.
-And space.

73
00:05:18,860 --> 00:05:22,030
My God, have you seen yourselves?
You all think you're so clever, don't you?

74
00:05:22,113 --> 00:05:23,240
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

75
00:05:23,323 --> 00:05:24,366
Yeah.

76
00:05:25,325 --> 00:05:28,328
Should take another 24 hours
which means we've got time to kill.

77
00:05:28,411 --> 00:05:30,205
That old lady's staring.

78
00:05:30,288 --> 00:05:33,959
Probably wondering what four people can do
inside a small wooden box.

79
00:05:34,042 --> 00:05:36,586
What are you captain of?
The Innuendo Squad?

80
00:05:38,421 --> 00:05:41,842
Wait, the Tardis, you can't just leave it.
Doesn't it get noticed?

81
00:05:41,925 --> 00:05:44,135
Yeah, what's with the police box?
Why does it look like that?

82
00:05:44,219 --> 00:05:46,763
-It's a cloaking device.
-It's called a chameleon circuit.

83
00:05:46,847 --> 00:05:48,974
The Tardis is meant to disguise itself
wherever it lands.

84
00:05:49,099 --> 00:05:52,185
Like, if this was ancient Rome,
it'd be a statue on a plinth or something.

85
00:05:52,269 --> 00:05:55,063
But I landed in the 1960s,
It disguised itself as a police box

86
00:05:55,188 --> 00:05:56,731
and the circuit got stuck.

87
00:05:56,815 --> 00:05:59,234
So, it copied a real thing?
There actually was police boxes?

88
00:05:59,317 --> 00:06:00,443
Yeah, on street corners.

89
00:06:00,527 --> 00:06:02,612
You could phone for help
before they had radios and mobiles.

90
00:06:02,737 --> 00:06:05,657
If they arrested somebody,
they could shove them inside till help came.

91
00:06:05,740 --> 00:06:08,702
-Like a little prison cell.
-Why don't you just fix the circuit?

92
00:06:08,827 --> 00:06:10,495
-I like it, don't you?
-I love it.

93
00:06:10,579 --> 00:06:13,081
But that's what I meant,
there's no police boxes anymore

94
00:06:13,164 --> 00:06:14,875
so doesn't it get noticed?

95
00:06:14,958 --> 00:06:17,836
Ricky, let me tell you something
about the human race.

96
00:06:17,919 --> 00:06:22,257
You put a mysterious blue box slap-bang
in the middle of town, what do they do?

97
00:06:22,340 --> 00:06:24,843
Walk past it.
Now, stop your nagging, let's go and explore.

98
00:06:24,926 --> 00:06:26,303
ROSE: What's the plan?
DOCTOR: I don't know.

99
00:06:26,428 --> 00:06:30,223
DOCTOR: Cardiff, early 21st century,
and the wind's coming from the...east.

100
00:06:30,307 --> 00:06:32,726
Trust me.
Safest place in the universe.

101
00:06:32,809 --> 00:06:36,479
This nuclear power station
right in the heart of Cardiff city

102
00:06:36,563 --> 00:06:38,607
will bring jobs for all.

103
00:06:41,985 --> 00:06:43,653
As you can see, as Lord Mayor,

104
00:06:43,737 --> 00:06:46,865
I've had to sanction
some radical redevelopments.

105
00:06:47,574 --> 00:06:49,951
No photographs!
What did I say?

106
00:06:50,035 --> 00:06:53,997
Take pictures of the project,
by all means, but not me, thank you.

107
00:06:54,581 --> 00:06:58,418
So, Cardiff Castle will be demolished,

108
00:06:58,501 --> 00:07:02,631
allowing the Blaidd Drwg project
to rise up, tall and proud.

109
00:07:03,381 --> 00:07:05,759
A monument to Welsh industry.

110
00:07:05,842 --> 00:07:08,470
And, yes,
some of you might shiver.

111
00:07:08,595 --> 00:07:11,932
The words "nuclear power station”
and "major population centre”

112
00:07:12,015 --> 00:07:15,060
aren't exactly
the happiest of bedfellows.

113
00:07:15,143 --> 00:07:20,440
But I give you my personal guarantee
that as long as I walk upon this Earth,

114
00:07:20,523 --> 00:07:23,401
no harm will come to any of my citizens.

115
00:07:24,527 --> 00:07:25,695
Now, drink up!

116
00:07:25,820 --> 00:07:28,406
A toast, to the future.

117
00:07:28,782 --> 00:07:30,200
ALL: To the future.

118
00:07:30,283 --> 00:07:32,827
And believe me...

119
00:07:32,911 --> 00:07:34,704
it will glow.

120
00:07:39,709 --> 00:07:43,046
Mrs Blaine, my name's Cathy Salt.
I represent the Cardiff Gazette.

121
00:07:43,129 --> 00:07:45,757
I'm sorry, I'm not doing interviews.
I can't bear self-publicity.

122
00:07:45,840 --> 00:07:49,511
-But are you aware of the curse?
-Whatever do you mean?

123
00:07:50,178 --> 00:07:51,930
-Cathy, wasn't it?
-Cathy Salt.

124
00:07:52,013 --> 00:07:53,932
That's what some
of your engineers are saying,

125
00:07:54,015 --> 00:07:55,809
that the Blaidd Drwg project is cursed.

126
00:07:55,892 --> 00:07:57,185
Sounds rather silly to me.

127
00:07:57,310 --> 00:07:59,980
That's what I thought,
I was just chasing a bit of local colour.

128
00:08:00,063 --> 00:08:02,524
But the funny thing is,
when you start piecing it all together,

129
00:08:02,607 --> 00:08:03,900
it does begin to look a bit odd.

130
00:08:04,025 --> 00:08:05,777
-In what way?
-The deaths.

131
00:08:05,986 --> 00:08:07,988
The number of deaths associated
with this project.

132
00:08:08,071 --> 00:08:11,533
First of all, there was the entire team
of the European Safety Inspectors.

133
00:08:11,616 --> 00:08:13,034
But they were French.

134
00:08:13,118 --> 00:08:15,954
It's not my fault if "Danger Explosives"
was only written in Welsh.

135
00:08:16,037 --> 00:08:18,665
And there was that accident
with the Cardiff Heritage Committee.

136
00:08:18,748 --> 00:08:22,460
The electrocution of that swimming pool
was put down to natural wear and tear.

137
00:08:22,544 --> 00:08:24,671
And then the architect?

138
00:08:24,879 --> 00:08:28,341
It was raining, visibility was low,
my car simply couldn"t stop.

139
00:08:28,425 --> 00:08:31,720
And then just recently, Mr Cleaver,
the government's nuclear adviser.

140
00:08:31,803 --> 00:08:33,388
Slipped on an icy patch.

141
00:08:33,471 --> 00:08:36,474
-He was decapitated.
-It was a very icy patch.

142
00:08:36,558 --> 00:08:39,978
I'm afraid these stories are nothing more
than typical small-town thinking.

143
00:08:40,061 --> 00:08:42,147
I really haven't got time.
If you'll excuse me.

144
00:08:42,230 --> 00:08:46,484
Except before he died, Mr Cleaver
posted some of his findings online.

145
00:08:46,568 --> 00:08:48,445
-Did he now?
-If you know where to look.

146
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:51,239
-He was concerned about the reactor.
-All that technical stuff.

147
00:08:51,322 --> 00:08:53,825
Specifically, that the design
of the suppression pool

148
00:08:53,908 --> 00:08:55,827
would cause the hydrogen
recombiners to fail,

149
00:08:55,910 --> 00:08:58,788
precipitating in the collapse
of the containment isolation system

150
00:08:58,872 --> 00:09:00,123
and resulting in a meltdown.

151
00:09:00,248 --> 00:09:03,293
-Who's been doing her homework?
-That's my job.

152
00:09:03,376 --> 00:09:06,546
I think...Cathy Salt...

153
00:09:07,714 --> 00:09:10,592
I think you and I
should have a word in private.

154
00:09:13,053 --> 00:09:14,137
(RUMBLING)

155
00:09:14,220 --> 00:09:16,556
Oh! My little tummy is complaining.

156
00:09:16,639 --> 00:09:19,059
I think we might have to
make a detour to the ladies'.

157
00:09:19,142 --> 00:09:22,687
-I'll wait here.
-Come on. All girls together.

158
00:09:24,147 --> 00:09:27,942
So, you were saying?
These outlandish theories of yours.

159
00:09:30,361 --> 00:09:32,155
(SQUELCHING)

160
00:09:32,238 --> 00:09:35,784
-Sounds like we got here just in time.
-Continue.

161
00:09:35,909 --> 00:09:39,370
Well, I don't know much about
nuclear physics,

162
00:09:39,496 --> 00:09:41,206
but from what I could make out,

163
00:09:41,289 --> 00:09:45,919
Cleaver was saying that the whole project
could go up, worse than Chernobyl.

164
00:09:49,130 --> 00:09:51,174
Is there something wrong with the lights?

165
00:09:51,257 --> 00:09:53,051
They're always on the blink.

166
00:09:53,134 --> 00:09:55,970
I can't tell you how many memos I've sent.

167
00:09:56,054 --> 00:09:58,223
So, Chernobyl?

168
00:09:58,306 --> 00:10:01,392
Apparently,
but a thousand times worse.

169
00:10:01,518 --> 00:10:05,188
I mean, it sounds absurd,
there must be so many safety regulations.

170
00:10:05,271 --> 00:10:08,983
But Cleaver seemed to be talking about
a nuclear holocaust.

171
00:10:09,067 --> 00:10:11,861
He almost made it sound deliberate.

172
00:10:11,986 --> 00:10:14,030
I mean, we're hardly the Sunday Times,

173
00:10:14,114 --> 00:10:15,365
we're only the Cardiff Gazette,

174
00:10:15,448 --> 00:10:18,034
but we still have a duty
to report the facts.

175
00:10:18,118 --> 00:10:20,912
And you're going to
print this information?

176
00:10:21,037 --> 00:10:22,705
Are you all right?
You sound a bit...

177
00:10:22,789 --> 00:10:24,249
Sore throat.

178
00:10:24,374 --> 00:10:26,126
(MARGARET COUGHING)

179
00:10:26,209 --> 00:10:28,169
Just a little tickle.

180
00:10:28,253 --> 00:10:32,006
But tell me, do you intend to make
this information public?

181
00:10:32,090 --> 00:10:33,466
I have to.

182
00:10:35,093 --> 00:10:36,886
So be it.

183
00:10:37,804 --> 00:10:40,598
Mind you,
my boyfriend thinks I'm mad.

184
00:10:41,599 --> 00:10:43,393
We're getting married next month

185
00:10:43,476 --> 00:10:46,104
and he says if I cause a fuss,
I could lose my job,

186
00:10:46,187 --> 00:10:48,189
just when we need the money.

187
00:10:48,314 --> 00:10:49,858
-Boyfriend?
-Jeffrey.

188
00:10:50,483 --> 00:10:53,945
Civil servant.
He's nothing exciting, but he's mine.

189
00:10:54,112 --> 00:10:56,739
-When's the wedding?
-The 19th.

190
00:10:56,948 --> 00:10:59,117
It's really just to stop my mother
from nagging,

191
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:02,370
but the baby sort of
clinched it, I suppose.

192
00:11:04,581 --> 00:11:06,583
You're with child?

193
00:11:08,501 --> 00:11:11,504
Three months,
it's not showing yet.

194
00:11:12,964 --> 00:11:16,843
Wasn't planned, it was an accident.
Nice accident, though.

195
00:11:17,343 --> 00:11:19,596
-Congratulations.
-Thank you.

196
00:11:20,430 --> 00:11:23,349
-How about you?
-No.

197
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:26,978
-Is there a Mr Blaine?
-Not anymore.

198
00:11:27,687 --> 00:11:29,439
I'm all on my own.

199
00:11:30,565 --> 00:11:33,151
I had quite a size able family
once upon a time.

200
00:11:33,234 --> 00:11:36,362
Wonderful brothers.
Oh, they were bold.

201
00:11:37,614 --> 00:11:39,699
But all of them gone, now.

202
00:11:41,075 --> 00:11:44,579
Maybe you're right.
Maybe I'm cursed.

203
00:11:44,746 --> 00:11:47,207
No, I don't think so, not really.

204
00:11:47,332 --> 00:11:49,042
You're very kind.

205
00:11:51,252 --> 00:11:53,963
If you don't mind,
I might be a while.

206
00:11:54,172 --> 00:11:57,634
You run along.
Perhaps we could do this another day.

207
00:11:58,051 --> 00:12:00,428
-Are you all right?
-Fine.

208
00:12:00,511 --> 00:12:04,515
Okay, I tell you what,
I'll leave my details with your office.

209
00:12:05,099 --> 00:12:06,893
Thanks for talking.

210
00:12:07,852 --> 00:12:09,229
Thank you.

211
00:12:19,864 --> 00:12:21,991
(LOW MOANING)

212
00:12:27,538 --> 00:12:30,500
JACK: I swear!
DOCTOR: You're lying through your teeth!

213
00:12:30,583 --> 00:12:34,254
It turns out the white things are tusks,
and I mean, tusks!

214
00:12:34,337 --> 00:12:35,838
And it's woken and it's not happy.

215
00:12:35,922 --> 00:12:37,215
How could you not know
it was there?

216
00:12:37,298 --> 00:12:39,467
We're standing there,
15 of us, naked.

217
00:12:39,550 --> 00:12:42,053
And I'm like,
"No, it's got nothing to do with me."

218
00:12:42,136 --> 00:12:45,056
And then it roars, and we're running.
My God, we are running.

219
00:12:45,181 --> 00:12:47,517
And Brakovitch falls
so I turn to him and I say...

220
00:12:47,600 --> 00:12:50,436
-I knew we should have turned left!
-That's my line!

221
00:12:51,479 --> 00:12:55,316
I don't believe you, I don't believe a word
you say, ever. That is so brilliant!

222
00:12:55,400 --> 00:12:56,985
Did you ever get
your clothes back?

223
00:12:57,068 --> 00:12:59,320
No, I just picked him up
and went right for the ship.

224
00:12:59,445 --> 00:13:02,949
Full throttle, didn't stop
tilL I hit the space lanes. I was shaking!

225
00:13:03,116 --> 00:13:06,286
It was unbelievable! Freaked me out.
And by the time I got there,

226
00:13:06,369 --> 00:13:09,789
I was 15 light years away
and I realised I'm like this...

227
00:13:09,872 --> 00:13:12,417
And I was having
such a nice day.

228
00:13:25,054 --> 00:13:26,556
According to Intelligence,

229
00:13:26,639 --> 00:13:29,267
the target is the last surviving member
of the Slitheen family.

230
00:13:29,350 --> 00:13:32,103
A criminal sect from the planet
Rexicoricophalvitorius

231
00:13:32,186 --> 00:13:34,939
masquerading as a human being,
zipped inside a skin suit.

232
00:13:35,023 --> 00:13:38,067
Okay, plan of attack.
We assume a basic 57-56 strategy,

233
00:13:38,151 --> 00:13:40,611
covering all available exits
on the ground floor.

234
00:13:40,695 --> 00:13:43,489
Doctor, you go face to face,
that'll designate Exit 1.

235
00:13:43,573 --> 00:13:46,284
I'll cover Exit 2.
Rose, you Exit 3,

236
00:13:46,367 --> 00:13:48,995
Mickey Smith, you take Exit 4.
Have you got that?

237
00:13:49,078 --> 00:13:51,331
Excuse me, who's in charge?

238
00:13:52,123 --> 00:13:54,959
Sorry, awaiting orders, sir.

239
00:13:55,460 --> 00:13:57,462
Right, here's the plan.

240
00:13:59,255 --> 00:14:01,549
Like he said.
Nice plan. Anything else?

241
00:14:02,175 --> 00:14:03,593
-Present arms.
-Ready.

242
00:14:03,676 --> 00:14:04,969
-Ready.
-Ready.

243
00:14:05,386 --> 00:14:06,471
-Speed dial?
-Yeah.

244
00:14:06,554 --> 00:14:07,597
-Ready.
-Check.

245
00:14:07,680 --> 00:14:09,515
See you in hell.

246
00:14:17,899 --> 00:14:19,901
Hello, I've come to
see the Lord Mayor.

247
00:14:19,984 --> 00:14:21,527
Have you got an appointment?

248
00:14:21,611 --> 00:14:24,238
No, just an old friend passing by,
bit of a surprise.

249
00:14:24,322 --> 00:14:25,823
Can't wait to see her face.

250
00:14:25,907 --> 00:14:28,242
Well, she's just
having a cup of tea.

251
00:14:28,326 --> 00:14:31,579
Just go in there and tell her
the Doctor would like to see her.

252
00:14:31,662 --> 00:14:32,872
Doctor who?

253
00:14:32,955 --> 00:14:36,584
Just the Doctor.
Tell her exactly that, the Doctor.

254
00:14:37,877 --> 00:14:39,462
Hang on a tick.

255
00:14:47,345 --> 00:14:48,805
(CUP SHATTERING)

256
00:14:55,269 --> 00:14:58,689
The Lord Mayor says thank you
for popping by.

257
00:14:58,773 --> 00:15:01,275
She'd love to have a chat

258
00:15:01,359 --> 00:15:03,361
but she's up to her eyes in paperwork.

259
00:15:03,444 --> 00:15:06,072
Perhaps if you could make an appointment
for next week?

260
00:15:06,155 --> 00:15:08,366
She's climbing out of
the window, isn't she?

261
00:15:08,449 --> 00:15:09,867
Yes, she is.

262
00:15:19,043 --> 00:15:21,087
-Slitheen heading north.
-On my way.

263
00:15:21,170 --> 00:15:22,630
Over and out.

264
00:15:23,840 --> 00:15:25,091
Oh, my God!

265
00:15:25,758 --> 00:15:27,301
Leave the Mayor alone!

266
00:15:34,183 --> 00:15:35,518
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

267
00:16:01,169 --> 00:16:02,920
Margaret!

268
00:16:09,552 --> 00:16:12,221
-Who's on Exit 47
-That was Mickey!

269
00:16:12,388 --> 00:16:14,182
-Here I am.
-Mickey the idiot.

270
00:16:14,265 --> 00:16:17,685
Be fair, she's not exactly
gonna outrun us, is she?

271
00:16:20,438 --> 00:16:23,566
She's got a teleport! That's cheating.
Now, we're never gonna get her!

272
00:16:23,649 --> 00:16:26,277
The Doctor's very good at teleports.

273
00:16:44,795 --> 00:16:46,631
I could do this all day.

274
00:16:46,714 --> 00:16:49,175
This is persecution.
Why can't you leave me alone?

275
00:16:49,258 --> 00:16:50,593
What did I ever do to you?

276
00:16:50,801 --> 00:16:53,638
You tried to kill me
and destroy this entire planet.

277
00:16:53,721 --> 00:16:54,847
Apart from that.

278
00:16:55,431 --> 00:16:58,184
So, you're a Slitheen,
you're on Earth, you're trapped.

279
00:16:58,267 --> 00:17:02,146
Your family get killed, but you teleport out,
just in the nick of time.

280
00:17:02,271 --> 00:17:04,440
You have no means of escape,
what do you do?

281
00:17:04,524 --> 00:17:07,485
You build a nuclear power station.
But what for?

282
00:17:08,069 --> 00:17:11,280
A philanthropic gesture.
I've learned the error of my ways.

283
00:17:11,364 --> 00:17:13,950
And it just so happens to be
right on top of the rift.

284
00:17:14,033 --> 00:17:16,744
-What rift would that be?
-A rift in space and time.

285
00:17:16,827 --> 00:17:20,373
If this power station went into meltdown,
the entire planet would go...

286
00:17:20,456 --> 00:17:24,168
This station is designed to explode
the minute it reaches capacity.

287
00:17:24,252 --> 00:17:25,753
Didn't anyone notice?

288
00:17:25,836 --> 00:17:28,297
Isn't there someone in London
checking this sort of stuff?

289
00:17:28,381 --> 00:17:31,175
We're in Cardiff.
London doesn't care.

290
00:17:31,259 --> 00:17:34,554
The South Wales coast could
fall into the sea and they wouldn't notice.

291
00:17:34,887 --> 00:17:39,892
Oh! I sound like a Welshman.
God help me, I've gone native.

292
00:17:39,976 --> 00:17:41,394
But why would she do that?

293
00:17:41,477 --> 00:17:43,688
A great big explosion,
she'd only end up killing herself.

294
00:17:43,771 --> 00:17:47,316
-She's got a name, you know.
-She's not even a she, she's a thing.

295
00:17:47,400 --> 00:17:49,110
Oh, but she's clever.

296
00:17:55,700 --> 00:17:56,909
Fantastic!

297
00:17:56,993 --> 00:18:00,204
Is that a tribophysical waveform
macro-kinetic extrapolator?

298
00:18:00,288 --> 00:18:02,290
Couldn't have put it better myself.

299
00:18:02,373 --> 00:18:05,293
Genius! You didn't build this?

300
00:18:05,376 --> 00:18:07,253
I have my hobbies,
a little tinkering.

301
00:18:07,336 --> 00:18:10,881
No, I mean, you really didn't build this.
Way beyond you.

302
00:18:10,965 --> 00:18:13,634
-I bet she stole it.
-It fell into my hands.

303
00:18:13,718 --> 00:18:16,137
-Is it a weapon?
-It's transport.

304
00:18:17,013 --> 00:18:21,934
You see, if the reactor blows, the rift opens.
Phenomenal cosmic disaster.

305
00:18:22,268 --> 00:18:24,937
But this thing shrouds you in a force-field.

306
00:18:25,021 --> 00:18:28,065
You have this energy bubble...
So you're safe.

307
00:18:28,149 --> 00:18:30,526
Then you feed it coordinates,
stand on top

308
00:18:30,610 --> 00:18:33,613
and ride the concussion
all the way out of the solar system.

309
00:18:33,696 --> 00:18:36,574
-It's a surfboard.
-A pan-dimensional surfboard, yeah.

310
00:18:36,657 --> 00:18:37,867
And it would've worked.

311
00:18:37,950 --> 00:18:41,621
I'd have surfed away from this dead-end dump
and back to civilisation.

312
00:18:41,704 --> 00:18:43,664
You'd blow up a whole planet
just to get a lift?

313
00:18:43,748 --> 00:18:46,000
Like stepping on an ant hill.

314
00:18:46,417 --> 00:18:48,252
How did you think of the name?

315
00:18:48,336 --> 00:18:51,464
What? Blaidd Drwg? It's Welsh.

316
00:18:51,547 --> 00:18:53,716
I know,
but how did you think of it?

317
00:18:53,799 --> 00:18:58,262
I chose it at random, that's all, I don't know.
Just sounded good.

318
00:18:58,512 --> 00:19:00,097
Does it matter?

319
00:19:03,392 --> 00:19:04,852
Blaidd Drwg.

320
00:19:05,186 --> 00:19:07,438
-What's it mean?
-"Bad Wolf."

321
00:19:08,105 --> 00:19:13,027
But I've heard that before. Bad Wolf.
I've heard that lots of times.

322
00:19:13,110 --> 00:19:16,072
Everywhere we go,
two words, following us.

323
00:19:17,073 --> 00:19:18,324
Bad Wolf.

324
00:19:18,407 --> 00:19:20,701
How can they be following us?

325
00:19:23,537 --> 00:19:24,955
No, just a coincidence.

326
00:19:25,039 --> 00:19:28,292
Like hearing a word on the radio
then hearing it all day. Never mind.

327
00:19:28,376 --> 00:19:31,045
Things to do. Margaret,
we're gonna take you home.

328
00:19:31,128 --> 00:19:33,506
Hold on, isn't that the easy option?
Like letting her go?

329
00:19:33,589 --> 00:19:36,592
I don't believe it,
we actually get to go to Rexi...

330
00:19:36,676 --> 00:19:39,595
Wait a minute, Rexicor...

331
00:19:39,679 --> 00:19:41,222
Rexicoricophalvitorius.

332
00:19:41,305 --> 00:19:43,557
-Rexicorico...
-Phalvitorius.

333
00:19:43,641 --> 00:19:46,560
-Rexicoricophalvitorius!
-That's it!

334
00:19:47,311 --> 00:19:48,479
I did it!

335
00:19:48,562 --> 00:19:50,815
They have the death penalty.

336
00:19:55,403 --> 00:19:59,323
The family Slitheen was tried
in its absence many years ago

337
00:19:59,407 --> 00:20:01,117
and found guilty.

338
00:20:01,367 --> 00:20:03,452
With no chance of appeal.

339
00:20:04,495 --> 00:20:08,499
According to the statutes of government,
the moment I return, I'm to be executed.

340
00:20:09,166 --> 00:20:11,669
What do you make of that, Doctor?

341
00:20:13,421 --> 00:20:16,340
Take me home and you
take me to my death.

342
00:20:16,549 --> 00:20:18,134
Not my problem.

343
00:20:25,307 --> 00:20:27,393
MARGARET: This ship is impossible!

344
00:20:28,602 --> 00:20:30,062
It's superb!

345
00:20:30,187 --> 00:20:32,732
How do you get the outside
around the inside?

346
00:20:32,857 --> 00:20:35,443
Like I'd give you the secret, yeah.

347
00:20:35,860 --> 00:20:38,487
I almost feel better
about being defeated.

348
00:20:38,571 --> 00:20:40,281
I never stood a chance.

349
00:20:40,364 --> 00:20:42,992
This is the technology of the gods.

350
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:45,411
Don't worship me,
I'd make a very bad god.

351
00:20:45,494 --> 00:20:47,830
You wouldn't get
a day off, for starters.

352
00:20:47,913 --> 00:20:49,832
Jack, how we doing, big fella?

353
00:20:49,915 --> 00:20:53,794
This extrapolator's top of the range.
Where did you get it?

354
00:20:54,378 --> 00:20:56,881
I don't know,
some airlock sale.

355
00:20:57,006 --> 00:21:00,968
Must've been a great, big heist.
It's stacked with power.

356
00:21:01,051 --> 00:21:04,096
-But we can use it for fuel?
-It's not compatible.

357
00:21:04,180 --> 00:21:06,807
But it should knock
off about 12 hours.

358
00:21:06,891 --> 00:21:08,184
We'll be ready to go
by morning.

359
00:21:08,267 --> 00:21:11,061
Then we're stuck here, overnight.

360
00:21:11,145 --> 00:21:12,563
I'm in no hurry.

361
00:21:12,646 --> 00:21:14,273
ROSE: We've got a prisoner.

362
00:21:14,356 --> 00:21:17,610
The police box is really a police box.

363
00:21:18,319 --> 00:21:20,738
You're not just police, though.

364
00:21:21,405 --> 00:21:25,701
Since you're taking me to my death,
that makes you my executioners.

365
00:21:27,077 --> 00:21:29,205
Each and every one of you.

366
00:21:30,372 --> 00:21:31,999
You deserve it.

367
00:21:33,250 --> 00:21:35,544
You're very quick to say so.

368
00:21:36,003 --> 00:21:38,839
And you're very quick
to soak your hands in my blood.

369
00:21:38,923 --> 00:21:42,051
Which makes you
better than me how, exactly?

370
00:21:44,178 --> 00:21:45,930
Long night ahead.

371
00:22:01,612 --> 00:22:04,281
Let's see who can
look me in the eye.

372
00:22:33,269 --> 00:22:35,271
It's freezing out here.

373
00:22:36,981 --> 00:22:38,858
Better than in there.

374
00:22:41,652 --> 00:22:45,114
She does deserve it,
she's a Slitheen, I don't care.

375
00:22:45,322 --> 00:22:48,576
It's just weird in that box.

376
00:22:50,035 --> 00:22:52,538
I didn't really need my passport.

377
00:23:01,088 --> 00:23:05,426
I've been thinking, you know,
we could go have a drink.

378
00:23:06,844 --> 00:23:09,638
Have a pizza or something,
just you and me.

379
00:23:09,722 --> 00:23:11,682
That'd be nice.

380
00:23:11,765 --> 00:23:15,436
And, I mean, if the Tardis
can't leave until morning...

381
00:23:18,731 --> 00:23:21,692
We could go to a hotel.
Spend the night.

382
00:23:21,859 --> 00:23:24,570
I mean, if you want to.
I've got some money.

383
00:23:24,653 --> 00:23:26,071
Okay, yeah.

384
00:23:26,196 --> 00:23:28,282
-Is that all right?
-Yeah.

385
00:23:31,118 --> 00:23:35,414
Cool, there's a couple of bars round here,
we should give them a go.

386
00:23:36,081 --> 00:23:38,459
Do you have to go and tell him?

387
00:23:38,626 --> 00:23:40,753
It's none of his business.

388
00:23:45,215 --> 00:23:46,759
So, what's on?

389
00:23:47,301 --> 00:23:49,219
Nothing, just...

390
00:23:53,557 --> 00:23:56,143
I gather it's not always like this.

391
00:23:57,561 --> 00:23:59,313
Having to wait.

392
00:24:05,319 --> 00:24:08,280
I bet you're always
the first to leave, Doctor.

393
00:24:08,405 --> 00:24:11,241
Never mind the consequences,
off you go.

394
00:24:11,450 --> 00:24:15,537
You butchered my family and then
ran for the stars, am I right?

395
00:24:16,080 --> 00:24:18,582
But not this time.

396
00:24:18,666 --> 00:24:21,043
At last, you have consequences.

397
00:24:23,504 --> 00:24:26,382
-How does it feel?
-I didn't butcher them.

398
00:24:26,465 --> 00:24:28,550
Don't answer back,
that's what she wants.

399
00:24:28,634 --> 00:24:30,552
I didn't. What about you?

400
00:24:30,636 --> 00:24:34,848
You had an emergency teleport,
you didn't zap them to safety, did you?

401
00:24:34,932 --> 00:24:36,809
It only carries one.

402
00:24:37,267 --> 00:24:39,144
I had to fly without coordinates.

403
00:24:39,228 --> 00:24:42,147
I ended up in a skip
on the Isle of Dogs.

404
00:24:42,231 --> 00:24:43,983
(DOCTOR LAUGHING)

405
00:24:44,066 --> 00:24:46,360
-It wasn't funny.
-Sorry.

406
00:24:50,364 --> 00:24:52,116
It is a bit funny.

407
00:24:57,079 --> 00:24:59,123
Do I get a last request?

408
00:25:00,124 --> 00:25:01,959
Depends what it is.

409
00:25:02,418 --> 00:25:05,170
I grew quite fond of
my little human life.

410
00:25:05,254 --> 00:25:07,006
All those rituals.

411
00:25:07,256 --> 00:25:11,218
The brushing of the teeth
and the complicated way they cook things.

412
00:25:11,343 --> 00:25:14,596
There's a little restaurant,
just round the Bay.

413
00:25:14,680 --> 00:25:17,307
It became quite a favourite of mine.

414
00:25:22,312 --> 00:25:25,774
-Is that what you want? A last meal?
-Don't I have rights?

415
00:25:25,858 --> 00:25:27,943
Like she's not gonna try to escape.

416
00:25:28,027 --> 00:25:31,989
Except I can never escape the Doctor
so where's the danger?

417
00:25:36,035 --> 00:25:38,328
I wonder if you could do it.

418
00:25:40,289 --> 00:25:44,251
To sit with a creature you're about to kill
and take supper.

419
00:25:47,129 --> 00:25:50,674
-How strong is your stomach?
-Strong enough.

420
00:25:51,008 --> 00:25:52,342
I wonder.

421
00:25:53,427 --> 00:25:55,929
I've seen you fight your enemies.

422
00:25:57,347 --> 00:25:59,183
Now dine with them.

423
00:26:00,809 --> 00:26:03,437
-You won't change my mind.
-Prove it.

424
00:26:07,149 --> 00:26:09,359
There are people out there.

425
00:26:09,693 --> 00:26:12,488
If you slip away just for one second,
they'll be in danger.

426
00:26:12,613 --> 00:26:15,199
Except, I've got these.

427
00:26:16,366 --> 00:26:17,868
You both wear one.

428
00:26:17,951 --> 00:26:20,746
If she moves more
than ten feet away...

429
00:26:22,790 --> 00:26:25,459
She gets zapped
by 10,000 volts.

430
00:26:26,752 --> 00:26:30,547
Margaret, would you like to come out
to dinner? My treat.

431
00:26:32,883 --> 00:26:34,635
Dinner in bondage.

432
00:26:36,970 --> 00:26:38,514
Works for me.

433
00:27:16,802 --> 00:27:20,472
Here we are, out on a date,
and you haven't even asked my proper name.

434
00:27:20,597 --> 00:27:22,266
It's not a date.

435
00:27:23,350 --> 00:27:25,435
-What's your name?
-Blon.

436
00:27:26,562 --> 00:27:29,565
I'm Blon Fel Fotch
Passameer-Day Slitheen.

437
00:27:31,275 --> 00:27:34,069
That's what it'll say
on my death certificate.

438
00:27:34,236 --> 00:27:36,780
-Nice to meet you, Blon.
-I'm sure.

439
00:27:38,866 --> 00:27:41,451
Look, that's where I
was living as Margaret.

440
00:27:41,577 --> 00:27:44,413
Nice little flat,
over there on the top.

441
00:27:45,247 --> 00:27:47,124
Next to the one with the light on.

442
00:27:47,249 --> 00:27:51,461
Two bedrooms, bay side view.
I was rather content.

443
00:27:51,962 --> 00:27:54,464
Don't suppose I'll see it again.

444
00:27:58,677 --> 00:28:00,137
Suppose not.

445
00:28:01,680 --> 00:28:03,765
-Thank you.
-Pleasure.

446
00:28:06,143 --> 00:28:09,730
Tell me, then, Doctor,
what do you know of our species?

447
00:28:10,105 --> 00:28:11,815
Only what I've seen.

448
00:28:11,899 --> 00:28:13,859
Did you know, for example,

449
00:28:14,026 --> 00:28:16,195
in extreme cases,

450
00:28:16,361 --> 00:28:19,323
when her life is in danger,

451
00:28:19,406 --> 00:28:22,701
a female Rexicoricophalvitorian
can manufacture a poison dart

452
00:28:22,784 --> 00:28:24,703
within her own finger.

453
00:28:25,037 --> 00:28:26,371
Yes, I did.

454
00:28:27,039 --> 00:28:28,624
Just checking.

455
00:28:29,708 --> 00:28:31,501
And one more thing.

456
00:28:31,793 --> 00:28:33,587
Between you and me...

457
00:28:40,594 --> 00:28:45,599
WHISPERING: As a final resort, the excess
poison can be exhaled through the lungs.

458
00:28:47,517 --> 00:28:50,187
That's better.
Now then, what do you think?

459
00:28:50,270 --> 00:28:52,356
Steak looks nice.

460
00:28:52,481 --> 00:28:54,149
Steak and chips!

461
00:28:59,071 --> 00:29:01,531
ROSE: The Doctor took me
to this planet a while back.

462
00:29:01,615 --> 00:29:03,492
It was much colder than this.

463
00:29:03,617 --> 00:29:05,786
They called it Woman Wept.

464
00:29:05,911 --> 00:29:08,205
The planet was
actually called Woman Wept

465
00:29:08,288 --> 00:29:10,749
because if you looked at it,
right, from above,

466
00:29:10,832 --> 00:29:14,503
it was like this huge continent,
like, all curved round.

467
00:29:14,586 --> 00:29:17,756
It sort of looked like a woman,
you know, lamenting.

468
00:29:17,839 --> 00:29:19,967
Oh, my God,
and we went to this beach, right.

469
00:29:20,050 --> 00:29:22,261
No people, no buildings,

470
00:29:22,511 --> 00:29:25,389
just this beach,
like, 1,000 miles across.

471
00:29:25,889 --> 00:29:29,184
And something happened,
something to do with the sun, I don't know,

472
00:29:29,268 --> 00:29:31,728
but the sea had just frozen.

473
00:29:31,812 --> 00:29:33,355
In a split second.

474
00:29:33,438 --> 00:29:36,942
In the middle of a storm, right,
waves and foam, just frozen,

475
00:29:37,025 --> 00:29:38,860
all the way out to the horizon.

476
00:29:38,944 --> 00:29:41,863
Midnight, right, we walk
underneath these waves,

477
00:29:41,989 --> 00:29:44,741
100 feet tall and made of ice.

478
00:29:44,825 --> 00:29:47,369
I'm going out
with Trisha Delaney.

479
00:29:50,372 --> 00:29:51,748
Oh, right.

480
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:54,459
That's nice.

481
00:29:55,711 --> 00:29:59,214
-Trisha from the shop?
-Yeah, Rob Delaney's sister.

482
00:29:59,589 --> 00:30:01,341
Well, she's nice.

483
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:04,428
-She's a bit big.
-She lost weight.

484
00:30:07,681 --> 00:30:09,516
You've been away.

485
00:30:09,599 --> 00:30:12,060
Well, good for you.
She's nice.

486
00:30:13,895 --> 00:30:17,899
-So, tell us more about this planet, then.
-That was it, really.

487
00:30:23,405 --> 00:30:25,907
Public execution is a slow death.

488
00:30:27,409 --> 00:30:32,122
They prepare a thin acetic acid,
lower me into the cauldron...

489
00:30:32,205 --> 00:30:33,707
and boil me.

490
00:30:34,624 --> 00:30:38,295
The acidity is perfectly gauged
to strip away the skin.

491
00:30:38,879 --> 00:30:43,008
Internal organs fall out into the liquid
and I become soup.

492
00:30:44,176 --> 00:30:45,844
And still alive.

493
00:30:47,137 --> 00:30:48,889
Still screaming.

494
00:30:49,139 --> 00:30:52,100
-I don't make the law.
-But you deliver it.

495
00:30:52,976 --> 00:30:54,978
Will you stay to watch?

496
00:30:55,937 --> 00:30:57,439
What else can I do?

497
00:30:57,564 --> 00:30:59,691
The Slitheen family's huge.

498
00:31:00,067 --> 00:31:03,695
There's a lot more of us,
all scattered off-world. Take me to them.

499
00:31:03,820 --> 00:31:05,572
Take me somewhere safe.

500
00:31:05,697 --> 00:31:08,450
-But then you'll just start again.
-I promise I won't.

501
00:31:08,533 --> 00:31:10,619
You've been in that skin suit too long.

502
00:31:10,702 --> 00:31:14,331
You've forgotten.
There used to be a real Margaret Blaine.

503
00:31:14,414 --> 00:31:17,042
You killed her and stripped her
and used the skin.

504
00:31:17,125 --> 00:31:20,170
You're pleading for mercy
out of a dead woman's lips.

505
00:31:20,253 --> 00:31:22,464
Perhaps I have got used to it.

506
00:31:22,547 --> 00:31:24,966
A human life, an ordinary life.

507
00:31:26,551 --> 00:31:28,470
That's all I'm asking.

508
00:31:30,514 --> 00:31:32,599
Give me a chance, Doctor.

509
00:31:34,309 --> 00:31:37,062
-I can change.
-I don't believe you.

510
00:31:39,523 --> 00:31:42,526
-So, what do you want to do now?
-Don't mind.

511
00:31:43,985 --> 00:31:46,405
We could ask about hotels.

512
00:31:46,488 --> 00:31:48,824
What would Trisha Delaney say?

513
00:31:48,990 --> 00:31:50,283
I suppose.

514
00:31:52,577 --> 00:31:54,788
There's a bar down there
with a Spanish name...

515
00:31:54,871 --> 00:31:56,289
You don't even
like Trisha Delaney!

516
00:31:56,373 --> 00:31:58,375
Is that right?
What the hell do you know?

517
00:31:58,458 --> 00:32:00,669
I know you and I know her

518
00:32:00,752 --> 00:32:02,671
and I know that's
never gonna happen.

519
00:32:02,796 --> 00:32:06,633
-So, who do you think you're kidding?
-At least I know where she is!

520
00:32:08,051 --> 00:32:09,803
There we are, then.

521
00:32:09,928 --> 00:32:12,931
It's got nothing to do with Trisha.
This is all about me, isn't it?

522
00:32:13,014 --> 00:32:14,433
You left me!

523
00:32:17,144 --> 00:32:19,438
We were nice, we were happy.

524
00:32:20,272 --> 00:32:22,816
And then what?
You give me a kiss and run off with him

525
00:32:22,941 --> 00:32:25,861
and you make me feel like nothing, Rose.
I was nothing!

526
00:32:25,944 --> 00:32:28,363
I can't even go out
with a stupid girl from a shop

527
00:32:28,447 --> 00:32:31,825
because you pick up the phone
and I comes running.

528
00:32:33,160 --> 00:32:35,704
I mean, is that what I am, Rose, standby?

529
00:32:35,787 --> 00:32:38,957
Am I just supposed to sit here
for the rest of my life waiting for you?

530
00:32:39,040 --> 00:32:41,251
-Because I will.
-I'm sorry.

531
00:32:50,886 --> 00:32:54,431
I promise you I've changed
since we last met, Doctor.

532
00:32:55,182 --> 00:32:57,601
There was this girl, just today.

533
00:32:58,477 --> 00:33:00,020
Young thing.

534
00:33:01,146 --> 00:33:04,649
And something of a danger.
She was getting too close.

535
00:33:04,858 --> 00:33:07,611
I felt the blood lust rising,
just as the family taught me.

536
00:33:07,694 --> 00:33:10,655
I was going to kill her without a thought.

537
00:33:11,156 --> 00:33:12,616
And then...

538
00:33:14,201 --> 00:33:15,660
I stopped.

539
00:33:17,245 --> 00:33:19,456
She's alive somewhere,
right now.

540
00:33:19,539 --> 00:33:22,501
She's walking round this city
because I can change.

541
00:33:22,584 --> 00:33:24,794
I did change.

542
00:33:24,878 --> 00:33:27,631
-I know I can't prove it.
-I believe you.

543
00:33:27,923 --> 00:33:30,550
Then you know I'm capable of better.

544
00:33:30,675 --> 00:33:32,385
It doesn't mean anything.

545
00:33:32,469 --> 00:33:34,679
I spared her life.

546
00:33:34,763 --> 00:33:37,724
You let one of them go.
But that's nothing new.

547
00:33:37,849 --> 00:33:40,227
Every now and then
a little victim's spared.

548
00:33:40,310 --> 00:33:43,438
Because she smiled.
Because he's got freckles.

549
00:33:43,897 --> 00:33:45,690
Because they begged.

550
00:33:46,525 --> 00:33:48,902
And that's how you live with yourself.

551
00:33:48,985 --> 00:33:51,530
That's how you slaughter millions.

552
00:33:51,988 --> 00:33:57,577
Because once in a while, on a whim,
if the wind's in the right direction...

553
00:33:57,702 --> 00:33:59,246
you happen to be kind.

554
00:33:59,329 --> 00:34:01,831
Only a killer would know that.

555
00:34:01,957 --> 00:34:03,416
Is that right?

556
00:34:03,500 --> 00:34:04,876
From what I've seen,

557
00:34:04,960 --> 00:34:08,838
your funny little happy-go-lucky life
leaves devastation in its wake.

558
00:34:08,922 --> 00:34:12,217
Always moving on
because you dare not go back.

559
00:34:12,300 --> 00:34:16,388
Playing with so many people's lives,
you might as well be a god.

560
00:34:18,306 --> 00:34:20,392
And you're right, Doctor.

561
00:34:21,017 --> 00:34:22,602
You're absolutely right.

562
00:34:22,769 --> 00:34:26,106
Sometimes, you let one go.

563
00:34:29,317 --> 00:34:30,777
Let me go.

564
00:34:37,075 --> 00:34:40,662
I'm not asking you to leave him
because I know that's not fair.

565
00:34:40,829 --> 00:34:43,373
But I just need something,
yeah, some sort of promise

566
00:34:43,456 --> 00:34:46,001
that when you do come back,
you're coming back for me.

567
00:34:46,084 --> 00:34:47,544
(RUMBLING)

568
00:34:47,669 --> 00:34:50,422
-Is that thunder?
-Does it matter?

569
00:34:50,505 --> 00:34:52,340
That's not thunder.

570
00:34:53,174 --> 00:34:55,844
In the family Slitheen,
we had no choice.

571
00:34:56,094 --> 00:34:58,680
I was made to carry out my first kill at 13.

572
00:34:58,763 --> 00:35:01,933
If I'd refused, my father would have fed me
to the Venom Grubs.

573
00:35:02,017 --> 00:35:05,312
If I'm a killer, it's because I was born to kill.
It's all I know.

574
00:35:05,395 --> 00:35:06,855
(RUMBLING)

575
00:35:06,980 --> 00:35:09,524
Doctor, are you even listening to me?

576
00:35:09,608 --> 00:35:12,110
-Can you hear that?
-I'm begging for my life.

577
00:35:12,235 --> 00:35:13,945
No, listen, shush.

578
00:35:20,785 --> 00:35:22,329
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

579
00:35:25,206 --> 00:35:26,791
Go on, then, run.

580
00:35:26,958 --> 00:35:29,711
It's him again, isn't it? It's the Doctor.
It's always the Doctor.

581
00:35:29,836 --> 00:35:33,048
It's always gonna be the Doctor.
It's never me!

582
00:35:34,090 --> 00:35:35,592
The handcuffs!

583
00:35:40,180 --> 00:35:43,975
-Don't think you're running away.
-I'm sticking with you.

584
00:35:44,100 --> 00:35:46,519
Some date this
turned out to be!

585
00:36:00,158 --> 00:36:02,744
It's the rift.
The rift's opening.

586
00:36:25,350 --> 00:36:27,769
DOCTOR: What the hell are you doing?
JACK: It just went crazy!

587
00:36:27,852 --> 00:36:30,980
It's the rift. Time and
space are ripping apart.

588
00:36:31,147 --> 00:36:33,650
The whole city's
going to disappear.

589
00:36:46,496 --> 00:36:48,289
(CRASHING)

590
00:37:08,560 --> 00:37:10,019
It's the extrapolator.

591
00:37:10,103 --> 00:37:13,481
I've disconnected it,
but it's still feeding off the engine.

592
00:37:13,565 --> 00:37:15,984
It's using the Tardis,
I can't stop it.

593
00:37:16,067 --> 00:37:18,486
Never mind Cardiff,
it's gonna rip open the planet!

594
00:37:18,570 --> 00:37:20,613
What is it? What's happening?

595
00:37:20,697 --> 00:37:22,782
Just little me.

596
00:37:25,535 --> 00:37:28,788
One wrong move
and she snaps like a promise.

597
00:37:28,872 --> 00:37:30,290
I might have known.

598
00:37:30,373 --> 00:37:34,419
I've had you bleating
all night, poor baby.

599
00:37:34,627 --> 00:37:35,837
Now, shut it.

600
00:37:35,962 --> 00:37:38,256
You, fly boy.

601
00:37:38,339 --> 00:37:40,842
Put the extrapolator at my feet.

602
00:37:54,689 --> 00:37:56,149
Thank you.

603
00:37:57,567 --> 00:37:59,444
Just as I planned.

604
00:37:59,736 --> 00:38:02,614
I thought you needed to blow up
the nuclear power station.

605
00:38:02,697 --> 00:38:06,367
Failing that,
if I were to be arrested,

606
00:38:06,451 --> 00:38:08,745
then anyone capable
of tracking me down

607
00:38:08,870 --> 00:38:11,831
would have considerable technology
of their own.

608
00:38:11,915 --> 00:38:16,878
Therefore, they would be
captivated by the extrapolator.

609
00:38:17,962 --> 00:38:21,132
Especially a magpie-mind
like yours, Doctor.

610
00:38:21,883 --> 00:38:25,970
So, the extrapolator was programmed
to go to Plan B.

611
00:38:26,679 --> 00:38:29,432
To lock on to the nearest alien power source

612
00:38:29,516 --> 00:38:31,643
and open the rift.

613
00:38:32,769 --> 00:38:35,814
And what a power source it found.

614
00:38:36,314 --> 00:38:38,316
I'm back on schedule.

615
00:38:39,901 --> 00:38:41,778
Thanks to you.

616
00:38:41,986 --> 00:38:44,656
The rift's gonna convulse,
you'll destroy the whole planet.

617
00:38:44,781 --> 00:38:46,449
And you with it.

618
00:38:48,076 --> 00:38:52,914
While I ride this board
over the crest of the inferno,

619
00:38:52,997 --> 00:38:55,124
all the way to freedom.

620
00:38:56,876 --> 00:38:59,128
Stand back, boys.

621
00:38:59,963 --> 00:39:01,548
Surf's up.

622
00:39:15,144 --> 00:39:18,314
Of course, opening the rift
means you'll pull this ship apart.

623
00:39:18,398 --> 00:39:19,983
So sue me.

624
00:39:20,650 --> 00:39:22,402
It's not just any old power source.

625
00:39:22,527 --> 00:39:24,904
It's the Tardis, my Tardis.

626
00:39:25,530 --> 00:39:27,532
The best ship in the universe.

627
00:39:27,615 --> 00:39:29,742
It'll make wonderful scrap.

628
00:39:30,118 --> 00:39:33,288
-What's that light?
-The heart of the Tardis.

629
00:39:33,746 --> 00:39:35,540
This ship's alive.

630
00:39:35,790 --> 00:39:37,792
You've opened its soul.

631
00:39:42,672 --> 00:39:46,843
It's...so bright.

632
00:39:48,219 --> 00:39:50,096
Look at it, Margaret.

633
00:39:50,930 --> 00:39:52,348
Beautiful.

634
00:39:52,765 --> 00:39:55,226
Look inside, Blon Fel Fotch.

635
00:39:56,352 --> 00:39:58,146
Look at the light.

636
00:40:28,343 --> 00:40:29,886
Thank you.

637
00:40:41,272 --> 00:40:44,150
Don't look,
stay there, close your eyes!

638
00:40:45,818 --> 00:40:48,321
Now, Jack, come on, shut it all down.
Shut down.

639
00:40:48,404 --> 00:40:52,367
Rose, that panel over there,
turn all switches to the right.

640
00:41:08,132 --> 00:41:10,426
DOCTOR: Nicely done.
Thank you, all.

641
00:41:11,052 --> 00:41:12,887
ROSE: What happened to Margaret?

642
00:41:12,971 --> 00:41:15,390
JACK: Must've got burned up.
Carried out her own death sentence.

643
00:41:15,473 --> 00:41:17,767
No, I don't think she's dead.

644
00:41:17,976 --> 00:41:19,435
Then where'd she go?

645
00:41:19,560 --> 00:41:23,314
She looked into the heart of the Tardis.
Even I don't know how strong that is.

646
00:41:23,398 --> 00:41:25,441
And the ship's telepathic,
like I told you, Rose.

647
00:41:25,525 --> 00:41:28,903
Gets inside your head,
translates alien languages.

648
00:41:29,904 --> 00:41:33,658
Maybe the raw energy can translate
all sorts of thoughts.

649
00:41:39,205 --> 00:41:41,833
-Here she is.
-She's an egg?

650
00:41:41,916 --> 00:41:44,836
-Regressed to her childhood.
-She's an egg?

651
00:41:45,044 --> 00:41:47,505
She can start again.
Live her life from scratch.

652
00:41:47,588 --> 00:41:49,674
If we take her home,
give her to a different family,

653
00:41:49,799 --> 00:41:52,301
tell them to bring her up properly,
she might be all right.

654
00:41:52,385 --> 00:41:54,429
-Or she might be worse.
-That's her choice.

655
00:41:54,512 --> 00:41:56,764
-She's an egg.
-She's an egg.

656
00:41:58,391 --> 00:42:00,101
Oh, my God, Mickey.

657
00:42:52,820 --> 00:42:56,407
We're all powered up, we can leave.
Opening the rift filled us up with energy.

658
00:42:56,532 --> 00:42:59,410
-We can go. If that's all right.
-Yeah, fine.

659
00:43:01,913 --> 00:43:04,540
-How's Mickey?
-He's okay. He's gone.

660
00:43:04,999 --> 00:43:07,919
Do you want to go and find him? We'll wait.

661
00:43:08,127 --> 00:43:10,421
No need. He deserves better.

662
00:43:11,714 --> 00:43:14,300
Off we go, then.
Always moving on.

663
00:43:14,634 --> 00:43:17,303
Next stop, Rexicoricophalvitorius.

664
00:43:17,762 --> 00:43:19,388
Now, you don't often get to say that.

665
00:43:19,472 --> 00:43:21,474
We'll stop by and pop her in the hatchery.

666
00:43:21,557 --> 00:43:25,645
Margaret the Slitheen can live her life again.
A second chance.

667
00:43:26,187 --> 00:43:27,855
That'd be nice.

668
00:43:32,610 --> 00:43:34,487
(WHOOSHING)

669
00:43:45,039 --> 00:43:47,083
You got chosen, you're a housemate.

670
00:43:47,166 --> 00:43:49,877
You're in the house,
isn't that brilliant?

671
00:43:50,002 --> 00:43:52,421
Welcome to the Weakest Link.

672
00:43:53,464 --> 00:43:55,633
We are giving you
a brand-new image.

673
00:43:55,716 --> 00:43:58,052
Why? Is there something wrong
with what I'm wearing?

674
00:43:59,262 --> 00:44:01,013
-What was that?
-She's been evicted.

675
00:44:03,850 --> 00:44:04,892
This isn't just a game.

676
00:44:04,976 --> 00:44:08,146
I need to find the Doctor,
he's here somewhere, he's always here!

677
00:44:08,271 --> 00:44:09,605
There's something else going on.

678
00:44:09,730 --> 00:44:11,899
MAN: We have contestants
outside the games.

679
00:44:11,983 --> 00:44:13,317
My Masters,
they fear the Doctor.

680
00:44:13,401 --> 00:44:14,777
Tell me, who are they?

681
00:44:14,861 --> 00:44:18,114
That's impossible,
I know those ships, they were destroyed.

682
00:44:18,197 --> 00:44:19,282
Obviously they survived.

683
00:44:19,407 --> 00:44:22,910
Alert. Alert. We are detected.

